We investigate the Learned Iterative Shrinkage-Thresholding Algorithm (LISTA)---a deep-unfolded architecture---for sparse channel estimation. On i.i.d.~Gaussian channels, LISTA's NMSE saturates at approximately $-25$~dB for SNR $\geq 10$~dB, trailing OMP by 13--33~dB and FISTA by 1--27~dB; on realistic ITU pedestrian and vehicular channels it achieves $-23$ to $-27$~dB while requiring no sparsity knowledge. FISTA with 20 iterations outperforms LISTA at all SNR levels without requiring training data. Under MMSE equalization (the standard in modern receivers), all estimators converge to similar BER at SNR $\geq 5$~dB ($p > 0.05$). Despite these NMSE limitations, a mechanism analysis reveals that LISTA concentrates $100.0\% \pm 0.0\%$ of estimation error on true tap locations (vs.~$95.2\% \pm 0.6\%$ for OMP and $92.4\% \pm 0.4\%$ for standard ISTA; mean $\pm$ std over 5 seeds), placing $267\times$ less error on non-support taps than OMP. An ISTA control experiment demonstrates that this concentration is partially generic to soft-thresholding ($92.4\%$) but LISTA's learned parameters enhance it to $100.0\%$. The mechanism generalizes to $K=10$ ($99.9\% \pm 0.1\%$) and ITU channels ($99.3$--$99.5\%$). Under ZF equalization, this error concentration provides tangible BER benefits for 16-QAM at SNR $\geq 15$~dB (Holm--Bonferroni corrected $p < 0.05$), reducing noise enhancement by $1.8\times$. Ablation with 20 seeds reveals all three learnable components are significant, with the per-layer threshold schedule dominant ($+14$--$18$~dB degradation) and $\mathbf{W}^{(k)}$ contributing $+1.24$~dB ($p < 0.001$). SNR-specific training mitigates the NMSE saturation, achieving $-31$~dB (a $6$~dB improvement). We contextualize the error concentration mechanism within approximate message passing (AMP) theory, noting that the connection between LISTA's learned weight matrices and the Onsager correction has been established by prior work (Liu et al., 2023; Borgerding et al., 2020).
